        <text x="200" y="158" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f87171" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.7">Shared: count</text>
        <text x="200" y="170" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f87171" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.4">(heap / global)</text>

        <!-- Arrows to shared -->
        <line x1="110" y1="110" x2="175" y2="140" stroke="#60a5fa" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <line x1="290" y1="110" x2="225" y2="140" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <h3>Race conditions</h3>
    <p>When two threads read-modify-write the same variable without coordination, the result depends on interleaving. This is a <strong>race condition</strong>. The outcome is non-deterministic. The fix is synchronization (next chapter).</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Simulating a race condition
; Two "threads" both increment a shared counter
; Without synchronization, interleaving can lose updates

(define shared-count 0)

; Thread 1 reads, increments, writes
(define (thread-increment! label)
  (let ((local (+ shared-count 1)))  ; read + compute
    ; In a real race, the other thread could run here
    (set! shared-count local)         ; write
    (display label)
    (display " set count to ")
    (display shared-count)
    (newline)))

; Sequential execution: no race
(set! shared-count 0)
(thread-increment! "T1")
(thread-increment! "T2")
(display "Sequential result: ") (display shared-count) (newline)

; Simulated interleaved execution (race!)
(set! shared-count 0)
(let ((t1-read shared-count)   ; T1 reads 0
      (t2-read shared-count))  ; T2 also reads 0
  (set! shared-count (+ t1-read 1))  ; T1 writes 1
  (set! shared-count (+ t2-read 1))) ; T2 writes 1, not 2!
(display "Interleaved result: ") (display shared-count)
; Lost update: expected 2, got 1
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Race condition demonstration
# In real threading, this would be non-deterministic

import threading

count = 0

def increment():
    global count
    for _ in range(100000):
        count += 1  # NOT atomic: read, add, write

# Sequential: always correct
count = 0
increment()
increment()
print(f"Sequential: {count}")  # 200000

# Threaded: race condition
count = 0
t1 = threading.Thread(target=increment)
t2 = threading.Thread(target=increment)
t1.start(); t2.start()
t1.join(); t2.join()
print(f"Threaded:   {count}")  # likely < 200000
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Critical sections</h3>
    <p>A <strong>critical section</strong> is the part of code that accesses shared resources. The goal: ensure that at most one thread is in its critical section at any time. Three requirements: mutual exclusion, progress (no unnecessary blocking), and bounded waiting (no starvation).</p>

